      <section id="how">
        <div class="container">
          <h2>How it works</h2>
          <h3>Fixed-point installations capture continuously. The curation pipeline turns raw captures into the library you query.</h3>
          <p>
            Skydock operates three classes of fixed-point capture
            installations, deployed at high-incident intersections in
            partner-host buildings. Captures run continuously during the
            operational envelope; the curation pipeline filters and scores
            them into the deliverable library.
          </p>

          <h4 class="subsection">Site deployment models</h4>
          <ul class="feature-list">
            <li>
              <span class="key">Model A — rooftop</span>
              <span class="val">High-resolution camera + edge compute + cellular uplink installed on a partner building rooftop overlooking the target intersection. Simplest regulatory path; primary V1 deployment model. 3 sites live by M6 of operations; 5 sites by M12.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <span class="key">Model B — tethered drone</span>
              <span class="val">LTE-tethered drone hovering 50-150m AGL indefinitely (no battery limit, power via tether). Simplified Part 107 path for tethered ops; no Remote ID requirement on tethered drones. Deployed when intersection geometry needs higher vantage. Sites added M12-M18.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <span class="key">Model C — drone-in-a-box</span>
              <span class="val">Persistent ground station that launches drones on schedule; drone returns for battery swap. Continuous capture via rotation. Requires BVLOS waiver for unattended ops; deployed post-waiver clearance in Phoenix and Austin expansion markets.</span>
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h4 class="subsection">Capture geometry</h4>
          <ul class="feature-list">
            <li>
              <span class="key">altitude</span>
              <span class="val">50-120m AGL depending on intersection geometry. Default 80m for signalized urban intersections.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <span class="key">field of view</span>
              <span class="val">Full signalized intersection or 130m corridor captured in a single frame. Sampling at 25-30 fps; agent tracking via YOLOv8 + ByteTrack.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <span class="key">production rate</span>
              <span class="val">~5,000 raw candidate scenarios per site-month. ~1,000 delivered per site-month after curation filter. At 5 active sites: ~60,000 scored scenarios added to the library per year.</span>
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h4 class="subsection">The curation pipeline (the moat)</h4>
          <p class="dim">
            Every captured candidate scenario runs through 5 independent
            scoring signals. A scenario must score in the top 20% on at
            least 2 of 5 signals to enter the delivered library. ~80% of
            raw captures are filtered out. This matches Waymo's WOD-E2E
            human-review acceptance rate (30%).
          </p>
          <ul class="feature-list">
            <li>
              <span class="key">criticality</span>
              <span class="val">Physics-derived from agent tracks &mdash; TTC (time-to-collision), PET (post-encroachment time), jerk thresholds, near-miss detection. Cheap, interpretable; references Westhofen et al. 2021 catalog.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <span class="key">epistemic uncertainty</span>
              <span class="val">Per-frame score against our baseline perception detector. The signal that drove the 16% → 5.5% collision-rate reduction in Mining the Long Tail (arXiv 2508.18397). Orthogonal to criticality.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <span class="key">corpus frequency</span>
              <span class="val">Rarity ranking vs the growing Skydock library &mdash; how unusual this scene-class + agent configuration is relative to corpus. Matches Waymo's WOD-E2E &lt;0.03% threshold methodology.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <span class="key">multi-agent interaction density</span>
              <span class="val">Number of distinct agent interactions per scenario, derived from agent track topology. Higher densities surface scenarios where prediction and planning models stress most. References InterHub methodology (Nature Scientific Data 2025).</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <span class="key">scene-class taxonomy match</span>
              <span class="val">Alignment with customer's OpenODD axes &mdash; what ODD bucket this scenario belongs to in your coverage model. Custom taxonomies onboarded in ~1 week.</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </section>

