      <section id="quality">
        <div class="container">
          <h2>Quality methodology</h2>
          <h3>Capture quality + long-tail scoring, transparent per scenario.</h3>
          <p>
            Every scenario's <code>metadata.json</code> includes two score
            blocks: a 0-100 capture quality score (agent visibility, coverage,
            class diversity), and the 5 independent curation signals from
            the pipeline so your QA team can filter the library by rarity.
          </p>
          <h4 class="subsection">Capture quality (0-100)</h4>
          <ul class="feature-list">
            <li>
              <span class="key">60 points</span>
              <span class="val">Agent visibility ratio &mdash; frames each agent was inside the capture FOV / total frames observed.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <span class="key">20 points</span>
              <span class="val">Agent coverage &mdash; saturated at 70% of spawned agents to reflect realistic FOV limits.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <span class="key">20 points</span>
              <span class="val">Agent class diversity &mdash; vehicle / pedestrian / cyclist representation.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <span class="key">multipliers</span>
              <span class="val">Altitude-resolution factor (1.0 at 80m AGL, decreasing above). Wind-shake factor (1.0 at ≤12 mph, decreasing above, 10% floor for tethered/drone-in-box sites).</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            <strong>Scenarios scoring below 70 are not added to the library.</strong>
            No exception, no opt-in. If we can't hit the quality bar, the
            capture stays internal.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

